english:
  title: 'Epitaph for the Tomb of the Duke of Ujeon, Posthumously Titled Munjong, of the Jeong Clan: With Preface'
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In recent times, when people speak of ages of great peace, they invariably speak of the reign of Myeongryung. Indeed, Yeongryung favored small men and brought about the calamity of Akyoung, while Chongryung enjoyed but brief years in power and suffered the rebellion of Choe Won. Only Myeongryung saw five years of tranquility throughout court and country—scholars flourished and people willingly submitted—which we may rightly call an era of modest prosperity.

    It was in such times that one who rose through the ranks of minor officials reached the position of Chancellor within four years. He was grave in his conduct and simple in his bearing, and early earned renown throughout the realm. The Duke of Ujeon, Jeong Munjong, surely deserves to be named foremost among such exemplars.

    When Hyeongryung first took the throne, following precedent, he dismissed ministers to their retirement. For thirteen years the Duke dwelt in leisure, spending his days in communion with mountains and waters, contented without external ambition. Hyeongryung came to esteem him greatly and enfeoffed him as Lord of Ilseong. Soon after, he was appointed Vice-Counselor of the Secret Chancellery and military administrator for the northeast frontier of Happo. Whether entering court as minister or departing to command forces, his reputation grew ever weightier. Yet when the present sovereign sought to employ this elder statesman, illness descended upon him. Alas! When he fell ill, I myself came to attend him, and though his condition seemed not grave, when I returned some months later, he could no longer receive visitors. When he departed this life, I went with Han Maengun of Sangdang to make offerings, but my own illness prevented me from joining the funeral procession—a sorrow I carry to this day.

    Now his sons and sons-in-law request that I compose this epitaph. How could I refuse?

    The Duke's name was Sado, his courtesy name lost to time, and his childhood name was Yangbil. After his examination success, he took the name Sadeu to avoid a taboo, changing it to his current name when serving Hyeongryung—signifying that whether in office or in retirement, one must embody the Way.

    The Jeong clan was a distinguished house of Yeonil. His great-grandfather, Gyunji, was posthumously appointed Grand Commandant of the Imperial Household and Prime Minister. His grandfather, Yun, served as Director of the Bureau of Ceremonies and as Compiler of Imperial Decrees. His father, Yu, held the rank of Vice-Minister of the Imperial Clan. His mother, née Chae, was elevated to Lady of Gyeongwon and was the daughter of the Senior Counselor Hyukgil.

    The Duke was born on the fifteenth day of the eleventh month in the year Mugo of the Yeonju era. From childhood he showed aptitude for learning, and as he matured, his poetry revealed a bold and spirited nature, earning him early fame among his peers. At nineteen, when Examiners Chae Hongchol and An Gyu presided over the civil service examination, he passed at his first attempt.

    In spring of the Gichuk year, he was appointed Inspector of the Historical Records Office, soon promoted to Assistant Clerk, then Recorder, and subsequently to a palace position. Through diligent service he was made Imperial Censor. From his entry into office to his promotion to Censor-in-chief took merely ten months—an extraordinary advancement.

    When Myeongryung ascended the throne in the year Gabin, the Duke was promoted from Censor directly to Vice-Minister of Military Affairs. The following spring he rose to Minister, and after but eighteen days was elevated to Vice-Director of the Board and Literary Master of the Academy. He received appointment as Editor of the Spring and Autumn Annals, retaining his ranks and offices.

    Within a year he was named to the Court Rank and Titles Directorate—again, a remarkable rise. Subsequently he advanced to Vice-Director and Chief Administrator of Personnel, then to Minister of Military Affairs. In the sixth month he was promoted to Minister of the Right with the rank of Senior Counselor. By year's end he became Senior Minister of the Right and co-director of the Historical Bureau. The following year he presided over the civil service examination, selecting ninety-two candidates including the later Minister Park Hyung, earning praise for identifying worthy men.

    He rose to Vice-Minister of Justice and Chief Minister of Administration, and in autumn to Minister of Defense with Cabinet rank. Shortly after, Myeongryung, intending to employ him greatly, appointed him to direct the History Bureau at the Secret Chancellery. From his first service as Counselor to entering the twin ministries took but twenty-two months—and the Duke was but thirty years old. Yet court opinion did not consider his advancement premature; his esteem in that age may thus be judged.

    In the year Byeongsin his mother passed away, and he kept vigil at her tomb for three years as custom demanded. When Hyeongryung learned of his filial devotion coupled with his steadfast service, he said: "Minister Jeong is both loyal in office and filial in heart. This pleases me greatly," and elevated him to Lord of Ilseong. Thereafter, whenever the throne sought counsel on important matters, the Duke was commanded first, for his righteousness and integrity were valued above all.

    That autumn he became Vice-Minister of the Secret Chancellery and co-director of the Historical Bureau. The following spring he served as Governor of Hanyang. Later, when called back to the capital as co-administrator of the Secret Chancellery, he was soon sent to govern the northeast frontier at Happo. In matters both military and civil, he proved equally adept, bringing harmony and benefit to the entire region. When Ujeonseong sought to execute the Minister of Justice Choe Yeong on capital charges and sent interrogators to carry out his investigation, the Duke stood firm against the injustice, refusing to yield. When his opposition was reported and brought before the throne, the Duke was stripped of his command.

    In the year Jeongmi he became Vice-Director of the Secret Chancellery. In Sinhae he was appointed Director of State Affairs. The following year he received the title Faithful and Meritorious Counselor. Subsequently he was appointed Field Commander and Inspector-General for the northeast frontier, titles under which military and civilian affairs were consolidated in his hands. Yet he managed both with such wisdom that people praise his stewardship to this day.

    In the year Gyechuk his title of merit was changed from Eminent to Loyal and Diligent. That winter he became Vice-Minister of the Secret Chancellery and Administrator of the Imperial Conference.

    When the present sovereign ascended the throne, the Duke was appointed Minister of Personnel, and soon after Minister of Education with responsibility for the Royal Academy, retaining his historical bureau offices. The following year he became Minister of Justice, and subsequently was enfeoffed as Lord of Ujeon (changed from Ilseong). His rank was elevated and his honorary title expanded to Loyal, Diligent, Righteous, and Meritorious Counselor.

    In the year Mugo, the Duke's sixtieth year completed its cycle; his integrity and honor remained unblemished. Yet illness is Heaven's will. On the fifteenth day of the ninth month in the year Gimi, he passed away at his residence at the age of sixty-two. The court attended to his funeral rites, and on the seventeenth day of the eleventh month he was interred at Yultchon. Alas! Many men of virtue do not attain long life, and even those granted years rarely see beyond their sixtieth spring—Heaven is indeed stingy with mankind.

    The Duke married twice. By his first wife, née Pae, daughter of the Vice-Minister Hyeongpo, he had two daughters: the elder married the Chief Administrator of Law Yi Yong; the younger married the Censor An Gyeonggong. By his second wife, née Jeong, daughter of the Senior Counselor Jeong Po, he had one son, Hong, who served as Vice-Director of the Historical Records Office. He had several grandchildren of both sexes. The Chief Administrator had no sons; the Censor had one son named Gyeongkim and two daughters, all yet young.

    His epitaph reads:

    Generous was the Duke of Munjong,
    Uniting both the civil and martial arts.
    In service to two great offices,
    Thirty years and more he labored.
    Since four sovereigns received his loyal heart,
    Clear and unblemished was his noble way.
    Modest yet not rigid,
    Bold yet never arrogant.
    Beautiful Duke of Munjong—
    Your name befits your deeds.
    Thousands of years descending hence,
    Men shall still revere this stone.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Myeongryung, Yeongryung, Chongryung, and Hyeongryung refer to Korean monarchs (reigns of Gongmin, Gongyang, U, and Seonggyeong respectively).
  - key: ''
    value: The 'calamity of Akyoung' (악양지화) refers to historical incidents of factional strife during the reign of King Gongyang.
  - key: ''
    value: The epitaph format follows classical Chinese tradition, combining biographical narrative with evaluative verse that celebrates the subject's virtues and accomplishments.
